  <static seed="1292" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions170.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{6}-5x^{5}+4x^{4}}{x^{6}-7x^{5}+6x^{4}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{x-4}{x-6}, x\ne 1\hbox{ and }x\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{6}-5x^{5}+4x^{4}}{x^{6}-7x^{5}+6x^{4}}} \amp = \frac{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-5x+4\right)}}{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-7x+6\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}}{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-6\right)}} \\
                     \amp = {\frac{x-4}{x-6}, x\ne 1\hbox{ and }x\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>x^{4}</m> and <m>x - 1</m> were crossed out, the domain conditions lost during the simplification are <m>x \ne 0</m> and <m>x \ne 1</m>.</p>
</solution>
